	<annotations>
		<text id="0" type="text/markdown" rect="(272.0, 331.0, 129.0, 159.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">**EDA** (always the first step)
</text>
		<text id="1" type="text/markdown" rect="(921.0, 240.0, 194.0, 75.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">**clustering** with NO previous standardization</text>
		<text id="2" type="text/markdown" rect="(1251.0, 43.0, 129.0, 96.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">**clustering configuration** (how many clusters?) --&gt; **2**</text>
		<text id="3" type="text/markdown" rect="(1257.0, 183.0, 102.0, 75.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">**best clustering execution**</text>
		<arrow id="4" start="(1405.0, 311.0)" end="(1348.0, 315.0)" fill="#C1272D" />
		<text id="5" type="text/plain" rect="(1428.0, 267.0, 150.0, 33.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">clusters 1 and 2 are separated by just the duration_sec column (whose scale dominates all the others')</text>
		<text id="6" type="text/markdown" rect="(676.0, 504.0, 243.0, 79.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">**clustering** with previous **standardization**</text>
		<arrow id="7" start="(647.0, 673.0)" end="(715.0, 659.0)" fill="#C1272D" />
		<text id="8" type="text/plain" rect="(455.0, 692.0, 237.0, 159.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">standardization of all columns' scales to the same scale (centered around 0 and with std-dev 1)</text>
		<text id="9" type="text/markdown" rect="(1026.0, 536.0, 180.0, 96.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">**clustering configuration** (how many clusters?) --&gt; **4**</text>
		<arrow id="10" start="(1219.0, 693.0)" end="(1160.0, 700.0)" fill="#C1272D" />
		<text id="11" type="text/markdown" rect="(1233.0, 552.0, 338.0, 453.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">4 clusters is BETTER than 2 clusters? Why? We usually don't have any **business measure** to claim that! We just have a **math** measure (*Silhouette score*).
BUT, our dataset were generated by Claude AI, and it added a key column (**suite_type**, ie, the type of the test case). This **IS** a business measure (we usually don't have because data usually are NOT generated by ourselves!), **not known** to k-means (as *filtered by the widget *select column* at the beginning of the flow*. And the number of possible values for the categorical variable *suite_type* is JUST 4!!!.

Of course, k-means is NOT able to give business names to the 4 clusters.
Thanks to standardization, k-means was able to **recover the underlying structure hidden in the original dataset (not shown to k-means)**.

In principle C1-C4 **correspond to the 4 types of *suite_test*!!**
</text>
	</annotations>
